title: Sister District Sonoma & Friends Phonebank
description:
## Let’s keep Virginia blue!

### Join Sister District Sonoma & Friends Virtual Phonebank every other Saturday morning, from 10:00AM to noon, starting on June 21. We will go weekly in October.

- This is a virtual phonebank with limited availability for in-person phonebanking. 
- We will send Instructions for in-person when you register.

Help our candidate, Kimberly Pope Adams, keep Virginia blue! She is someone who knows the value of hard work, and never backs down from a fight. As a lifelong Virginian and a state government auditor of 20 years, she knows how to identify the misuse of taxpayer dollars, and is determined to work with community leaders and constituents to increase government transparency for all Virginians. In 2023, she lost her race by the tightest margin in the state-- 53 votes. In 2025, she's back, not just to get the job done, but to do it right. 

**Virginia is having a general election in 2025, and keeping the majority in the House of Delegates is crucial.**

After flipping the Virginia House of Delegates in 2023 by only 975 votes, we must help protect the Democratic majority to continue safeguarding democracy, especially with the growing threats coming from the federal government. Keeping the Dem majority ensures that Virginia remains a firewall against right-wing extremism and a leader in expanding economic opportunity, protecting freedoms, and defending democracy. A strong performance in Virginia this year will not only protect and expand the rights of Virginians, but also generate national momentum, inspiring Democratic successes in the 2026 midterms. 

### Why phonebank: 
The data proves it: phonebanking is THE BEST volunteering option for remote voter contact. We identify supporters and let them know why their vote matters, speak with undecided voters, and recruit local volunteers. We also help improve our candidate’s data! 

### Come one, come all: 
No experience necessary. Each Zoom phonebank includes training and check-ins for first-timers (experienced callers can jump right in). Our veteran phonebank leaders will help you get comfortable, increase your effectiveness, and make sure you have a great experience.

Light refreshments will be provided. 

About the Ohio Coalition for Equity & Adequacy of School Funding: This organization has been working since 1990 to ensure fair and adequate funding for all Ohio public schools and is currently challenging the constitutionality of the EdChoice voucher program.
All members of the public are encouraged to attend this important event.

title: Pramila Jayapal's Resistance Lab: Virtual Organizing Training 1.0
description:
*Interested in hosting an organizing training with your friends and family on June 1st? We'll show you how! Simply fill out this form: https://forms.gle/RXZwieKnLNkyYUox8. Once submitted, a member of our team will reach out with all the tools and resources you need to host a successful training.*

This session will cover our Resistance Lab 1.0 curriculum. If you missed the first session, this is for you!

The Resistance Lab is a series of trainings that are developed specifically for this moment. In this first lab, we look at how non-violent movements around the world have responded to leaders who seize power in authoritarian ways and the most effective tools and tactics to utilize in these moments.  We offer frameworks to understand this moment at home, and incorporate interactive conversation with others to help create community and build our resistance movement.   

The Resistance Lab was developed with experts who have researched and studied democratic backsliding around the world as well as in the United States and the non-violent movements that have emerged to challenge those authoritarian leaders.  We also draw from many toolkits for effective tactics and frameworks as well as from Pramila’s own background leading successful organizing movements for economic and social justice for two decades.  

Our goals are to help people understand how democracies fall and the most effective resistance movements that have challenged authoritarians and dictators; to turn anger, fear and frustration into action in the short-term while also preparing for a coordinated resistance movement for the longer term; and to build community across the country that can help grow our movement.  At the end of the day, we want to get people strike-ready and street-ready and make sure we protect our people, our freedoms and our democracy.  

With Trump and his MAGA billionaires doubling down on their attacks on the economic livelihoods of people to thrive and on our democracy, we can’t afford to sit this moment out. This is about building real power together. And it starts with you. 

RSVP today to secure your spot! You’ll receive the virtual event link closer to the date.

Sign up for our Resistance Lab Rapid Response email list to stay informed with the latest updates, click here to join: www.pramilaforcongress.com/the-resistance-lab

re Board of Supervisors:

The County Board of Supervisors are elected to four-year terms and provide direction to the County Administrator and several other county departments. 

The board is like the City Council, except its jurisdiction covers all the county and unincorporated areas. 

Board members decide the county tax rate and approve the county budget. 

The County Board of Supervisors oversees health, road, parks, libraries, law enforcement, and other municipal services. The Board also has the power to fill vacancies in the county and legislative offices, other boards and commissions, pass resolutions, and enact ordinances and regulations as authorized by state law. 

The Board has the authority to make decisions on a variety of issues, such as zoning changes, resolutions, and ordinances. 

Additionally, the board of supervisors has the power to remove and replace election precincts, appoint election inspectors and judges as well as canvass election returns, declare election results, and issue certificates.

title: Deep Canvassing Training and Canvassing in Oregon's CD-5

location.venue: Waverly Heights United Church of Christ

description:
Indivisible Oregon and Indivisible Cedar Mill are conducting comprehensive and experiential trainings in “deep canvassing,” followed by actual canvasses with voters in Oregon’s Congressional District 5. Our goal is to encourage voters to tell us what issues are most important to them. This information is critical to helping candidates understand their constituent’s most important concerns so that candidates can shape policy messages that address voters in more meaningful and effective ways.

Deep canvassing is a method of voter outreach that involves having authentic, empathic conversations with individuals about how they want government to serve them. Unlike traditional canvassing, which uses a script designed to persuade voters to support a candidate or cause, deep canvassing fosters a more comprehensive and genuine way of connecting with voters. The ultimate goal is to build a sincere relationship with voters by nonjudgmentally understanding their values, beliefs, and experiences rather than just gathering data through short conversations.

This is a 3-hour training followed by 1 hour of canvassing.  Afterward, trainees will be able to canvass on their own, or with a buddy, as often as they choose. Canvassing events will be scheduled regularly throughout June – September 2025.

title: Sister District Portland+ & Friends Phonebank!
description:
## Let’s keep Virginia blue!

### Join Sister District Portland+ & Friends Virtual Phonebank every Saturday morning, from 11:00AM to 12:30PM, starting on May 10th. 


Help our candidate, Lily Franklin keep Virginia blue! A former high school math teacher and Chief of Staff for VA Delegate Sam Rasoul, Lily Franklin has long been a dedicated advocate for affordable housing, accessible childcare, and quality education. Help us elect Democratic challenger Lily Franklin to defend and expand our one seat majority in the Virginia House of Delegates!

**Virginia is having a general election in 2025, and keeping the majority in the House of Delegates is crucial.**

title: Four Corners in Lenexa  Standing Rally
description: As citizens, we can’t let the policies and actions of the Federal Government and unelected billionaires be normalized, but we can only stop what’s going on by coming together.  A STANDING RALLY  will draw attention to the situation, encouraging our neighbors to join with us. We will rally every Saturday morning from 11 AM – 12 PM.  Stay for the full hour or come by when and for how long you can. We will peacefully line the sidewalk on all four corners of 87th Parkway and Maurer Road,  holding signs on issues that are most meaningful to us or just simply standing in support of our neighbors and our country.  If sitting is more comfortable for you, you are very welcome to bring mobility or lawn chairs!! There is room for everyone!
accessibility_notes:
Here are a couple of notes on logistics.
Please be especially mindful of parking.  For example, if you live relatively nearby, please consider walking.  If you drive, there is street parking on the residential streets to the north and also a bit further on the south.  About ½ mile down on the west, there is a large civic campus garage at 17201 W 87th St. Pkwy.  In addition, on the SE, SW, and NW sides of the intersection, there are restaurants and shops with big, but commercially owned parking lots meant for customers.  (Please note that if you become a customer, it’s fine to bring snacks to the rally that you have bought, but please take any empty snack containers back home with you, when you leave. In any case, no matter which direction you are coming from, if it is possible, please try to park before you reach the intersection to save on congestion and choose a spot as far away as you feel comfortable walking from, leaving closer spots to those who can’t walk as far.
The rally will start on the SE corner, but as more folks arrive, we will disperse to the SW, NW, and NE corners, as well.   If you cross from one side to another, please pay particular attention to cars turning right as you cross! 
 Participants should bring their own signs (if they want to hold them).  Note that sticks supporting the signs can’t be pointed at either end.  Also, in designing content for the signs, please remember that children will be present.  
Please stand only along the sidewalks parallel to the street and not on the grass.  However, also be sure to allow pedestrian access to the sidewalk and businesses.   We are not expecting issues, but keep in mind that a core principle behind our events is a commitment to nonviolent action.  Remember to de-escalate any potential confrontation with someone,  who disagrees with you. And of course, follow directions from our excellent Lenexa police, if asked.
We will not have speakers. The plan will simply be to hold the signs we have made and wave, if that feels right.  We expect that a lot of passing cars will honk back in approval! 
Finally, please note that all our organizers will be wearing lanyards with badges reading  “Standing Rally Corner Captain or “Standing Rally Media/City Liaison”.  If you see other folks with “Press” marked on their clothing or who are giving direction to you, know that they are not part of Four Corners and are not endorsed or vetted by us.
See you soon.  Let’s show our neighbors “what Democracy Looks Like”!!
P.S.  If you want to post an inspiring (!) story about your experience, please add #FourCornersinLenexa to your post!

location.venue: Reach and Teach Books, Toys, and Gifts

description:

This presentation will inform you and give you some tools to help heal from the stress.  Come as you are.  Come as a couple, or with your adult children.  Just come.

Pao herself was a powerful advertising executive from a leading firm in New York City.  When she became burnt out and depressed she did not follow the typical path; instead, she reached for the best global practices to help heal her.  She became a health coach in the process and sees clients from around the world, and has a strong presence in Silicon Valley.
